Since the outbreak of the COVID-19, people in Wuhan have become something of a bogeyman. The search for Wuhan people began everywhere, and the myth that followed grew. In today's letter, the shanghai-based author tells us about a bizarre adventure in the "search for a Wuhan car" , the process is ironic, but the ending is unexpected.

My Spring Festival treasure hunt: find a car in Wuhan

I want to cry

At 11:30 p.m. , r asked me out.

Going on a treasure hunt?

Treasure Hunt?

Find the Wuhan car.

I looked out of the window. It wasn't raining hard, so I told him I'd meet him at the gate in ten minutes.

By the time I left the neighborhood, R was standing on the side of the road, alone on the street.

No, there's nothing there. R waves to his neighborhood.

I met R in a game group, and it turns out he lives across the street. After the outbreak began, all kinds of groups became epidemic groups, and the names of the groups also became "biochemical crisis XXX" , "the god of death came XXX" , "the whole people fought against the epidemic XXX" . In the groups, all kinds of people fell down in the street, closed the roads, arrested people, and news of the dead was flying everywhere. Everyone was competing for hair, whoever has the latest news is the best. Of course, more than the news from the outside to cattle, is to personally catch a Wuhan car, Wuhan car photos to the group, we want to wow a piece.

Treasure Hunt. It's like a spring outing.

It's not that easy to find. I might have one the other day, but not today. I walk and talk, so to speak, but Wuhan car, I would like to look for one to see.

We're GONNA divide and conquer, and I'm GonNa take this half, and R's GonNa run across the street, and he's GonNa take care of each other.

The Rain said not big, but since New Year's Day has not stopped. My running shoes aren't waterproof. They look at the puddles.

Shanghai A, Shanghai M, Shanghai G, Shanghai B, Shanghai H, Shanghai F, Shanghai D, Shanghai L, Shanghai J... Su A, Su e, Zhejiang, Anhui, and many other things come out, but there is no Wuhan car.

Look, Land Rover, R said.

Wuhan car? I asked.

Shanghai A.

What's the big deal.

Two or three traffic lights down the road, there was no traffic, and R ran across the street.

No?

How can there be!

Hey, why don't we go over there? R looked across the road and smirked.

What for? You want to die. A couple hundred yards further on is Putuo District's designated fever clinic, which we can't even get around in time.

They must have Wuhan cars there. Don't believe in bottle drinks.

No.

We were talking and the pole in the hospital parking lot was lifted. One, two, two ambulances drove noiselessly onto the road, flashing Blue Lights, heading for Jing'an Temple.

You follow them. I mean, there's got to be.

Ouch, ouch, said R.

Follow me. I'm going the other way to the hospital. R's not talking. Stay close.

We walked across a long bridge, under which was a super complex, said to house ten thousand people. We did not enter the community, continue to move forward, to line 4 under the viaduct and then to the West. Once I saw three Xinjiang men walking side by side on the sidewalk, their hands behind their backs, holding silver, gleaming metal sticks.

A few hundred meters down the road, my brain's Wuhan car radar crackled, my intuition here can find something.

Yeah, yeah, it looks like it. R's looking both ways.

We quickened our pace and became more focused.

A white car was parked far away in a lane next to the market. My heart was pounding before I could read the license plate.

It's a Wuhan car! We'll run to it. Wow, IT'S A WUHAN CAR!

It was a white car, half-new and half-worn, with the front sign like a standing lion and two outstretched hands.

What brand is this? R asked.

Yes, I have... and I can't give you a name.

I took out my mobile phone to take a photo, and then I found a problem. Oh, this is not a Wuhan car. I said, this is ej.

Where is e j? R asked.

It's not Wuhan. Shanghai J is Shanghai, but Hubei J is definitely not Wuhan, Wuhan is Hubei A, but the whole Hubei is closed, this car should also escape.

I look around, it's a dump, and whoever's driving this e-j must be living in one of the seedy hostels right next door.

We were staring at Hubei J, and we didn't know what to do.

I don't want to call the 110. R has been acting like a guilty conscience, really unlike the Shanghai Man.

WHO said anything about a 110, I said.

Where's your Napkin? I reached out to R.

R pulled a crumpled packet of Napkins out of his pocket and handed them to me. I pulled one out and crouched down to dip into a puddle on the floor. Originally prepared to make a hand dirty water, but the water in the puddle is very clear, like just poured pure water. The streetlights glinted in the PUDDLE, more transparent than they appeared.

I will be soaked in Water Napkin to the car on a shake, the paper napkin slanted on the license plate, just block off the "e" word, and not a little deliberate.

WHOA, Whoa, whoa. R's looking around.

R immediately straightened up and said, nothing, nothing.

We looked at this car several times, pasted off the Hubei it does not have Wuhan car feeling at all. We walked thirty meters out of the Path, R said, forgetting to take a picture.

What's the point? It's not a Wuhan car. I said I was, and I kind of regretted not taking the picture.

The rain became so heavy that we were in no mood to hurry back. We can look anywhere on the way. Shanghai M, Suzhou B, Anhui a, Guangdong a, all of them.

At a casual glance, the car was parked in a gap five or six meters deep, just four hundred meters away from the compound. One side of the building materials city has been closed, on the other side of the scattered old residential buildings.

Hello, Hello, my name is R, Hubei A, Hubei A.

The car stopped in the gap five or six meters deep, outside a few debris oblique block. A square plank of wood, palm-wide, stood against the wall, with an iron nail at eye-level, on which hung a tin-can. White light shone from the back of the residential building, and at first glance the shadows of the wooden stakes and cans painted a very standard cross on the wall.

It was only when I saw the cross that I noticed the car inside.

The Real Hubei a! R was so excited, he took out his phone and took a picture. What kind of car is this?

R circled the car, taking pictures. I said stop taking pictures and put them back together.

There were only two Napkins left, and we each took one, and we dipped it in water and threw it on the license plate. I didn't get it right the first time. I peeled it off and shook it again to naturally block the jaw.

Somehow, this orange crystal sharp than just a lot of gray white car, so many days of rain or a flutter of gray.

I just found out now that this is the first Wuhan Car I've ever seen in my life.

I don't know Wuhan very well. I haven't been there once. It took me a while to come up with a story from seven or eight years ago. At that time I worked in Guangzhou, met a girl working in the newspaper, her face is not as sharp as Shanghai girls, not as round as Guangzhou Girls, is sharp and round very good-looking. When I asked her where she was from, she said Wuhan. Later we do not know how to talk about the love, walking together in Guangzhou, mountain climbing, by boat. She said, "later, I'll take you to East L. . I'll take you to fruit lake. Eat this, eat that. " . Then out of nowhere, out of nowhere, comes a returnee boyfriend, a childhood sweetheart, a fiance, and we're done. This is the only fate between me and Wuhan. Based on my understanding of her, if she returned to Wuhan, she would certainly be able to enter that kind of high-level circle. The first time she got news, the first time she ran away, perhaps she would indeed run to Shanghai, but not in a cheap car like this. Anyway, I'm not too worried about her.

I'm a little worried about where the people who drove this little car are staying, with all the demolition going on, no hotels, no guest houses.

R shook his hand and wiped the water on the outside of his sweatpants.

On a whim, I let go of my umbrella, spread my arms, and leaned over the front of the car.

Holy Shit, it's not dusty. R pulled out his phone and took pictures of me. WHOA, Whoa, it's dark.

Ear to the hood of the car for a split second, the image popped into my head, and I saw the guy in the car. The driver is a young mother, the father sitting in the back, wow, there are two children, a seven or eight-year-old brother, um... short hair, wearing a sky blue down jacket, a two-or three-year-old sister, mushroom head, wearing a pink sweater. Well, that's the family. That's the instinct.

The only thing I'm proud of, I guess, is my gut. When I used to play Werewolf kill on my phone, I used to call out three werewolves in the first round on a hunch. Other people always jump at the chance to accuse me of cheating and say I'm open. And I said, "you think this is a game of logic? "? No, it's a game of intuition. Listen. Listen. Who's the good guy? WHO's the liar? It's all in the voice. It's like those sensitive doctors who put a stethoscope on a person's chest and know who's sick and who's not. It's all in the sound.

I pricked up my ears and heard the rain pattering on the hood.

You can still smell the dust through your mask. How far are Wuhan and Shanghai? It's got to be 1,000 kilometers, so that's 1,000 kilometers of Ash. I thought, turning my face away to smell it again.

Holy Shit. Hugs and kisses. The "R" never stops. Tsk, Tsk, Tsk, Tsk, Tsk.

This mask is going back anyway to throw away, then there are six, today the second day, to restore logistics in five days. The family that drove up in the car had a couple of masks? Kids can't use grown-up masks. I can't stop thinking about it.

R and Flash, stabbed my eyes sour, I jumped up to say good, hurry back to take a shower, cold have no place to see.

Don't post any pictures of the car out there. I pulled off my mask and shouted. The pure air is like the woods after the rain.

R made a victory gesture and ran away.

People want to arrest Wuhan People, I have to let them live here well, even if more than a day, an hour, a minute.
